# SEQUENCE VI — ARRIVAL

EXT. CALABAR AIRPORT - ARRIVALS EXIT - AFTERNOON

The terminal doors open.

Heat takes the brothers before the country can.

MALIK, ADE and KAI step beneath the arrivals awning with BODE.

Four men compressed by a journey we did not see.

Travel shows anyway.

In their clothes.

In their eyes.

In the silence between them.

Malik carries a padded case against his chest.

Inside:

The sealed BIRCH TRAVEL URN.

Solomon, cleared for one last arrival.

The polished brass urn is wrapped inside Malik's carry-on.

Ade drags a suitcase marked with a red strap.

Kai lifts his camera.

Humidity clouds the lens before he can frame anything.

ADE
So this is air now.

BODE
You will adjust.

ADE
Was hoping the air would.

Bode scans the pickup lane.

Cars.

Drivers calling names.

Families recognizing one another across traffic.

Then—

A hand-painted placard rises above the crowd:

OKU — FOUR.

Bode sees it.

The tension in his face loosens by one degree.

BODE
Come.

Kai wipes a clear circle into the fogged lens.

Through it:

The sign.

The waiting road.

A country their father made into a silence.

The four men step into the heat.

CUT TO:

# SEQUENCE VII — THE ROAD HOME

EXT. CALABAR AIRPORT - PICKUP LANE - CONTINUOUS

The hand-painted placard lowers.

Behind it stands EYO OKU, 51.

Lean.

Pressed short-sleeved shirt already darkening at the collar.

Car keys looped around one finger.

The patient posture of a man who has spent years keeping other people's things alive.

He looks at Bode.

Relief reaches his face first.

Then judgement.

EYO
Bode Oku.

You still remember road?

BODE
You came to the airport.

EYO
Because you forgot it.

They embrace.

Not ceremonially.

Hard.

Years compressed into a few seconds neither man will discuss.

When they separate, Eyo keeps one hand on Bode's shoulder.

Checks him.

Older.

Thinner.

Still here.

Then he turns to the brothers.

He does not ask who is who.

EYO
Malik.

Malik shifts the padded carry case into his other hand.

EYO
Ade.

Ade offers a tired salute.

EYO
And Kai.

Kai's camera hangs uselessly beneath its fogged lens.

ADE
Were there photographs?

EYO
Bode talks when he is worried.

BODE
I gave names.

EYO
You gave reports.

Eyo studies Malik's document case.

Ade's red-strapped suitcase.

Kai's camera.

Three reports confirmed.

His attention settles on the padded carry case.

The humour leaves him.

EYO
And this is Brother Solomon.

Malik looks at the case.

MALIK
His ashes.

EYO
I know what you carried.

Eyo reaches for one handle.

Malik does not release it.

A beat.

MALIK
I have him.

Eyo recognizes the grip.

Does not challenge it.

EYO
Then hold am well.

The road has not improved for anybody.

He takes Ade's suitcase instead.

EYO
Una welcome.

Come.

Make we move before this sun roast person.

ADE
It has started with me.

EYO
That one na airport.

Calabar never start.

EXT. CALABAR AIRPORT - PARKING AREA - MOMENTS LATER

An older TOYOTA LAND CRUISER waits beneath a flame tree.

Clean.

Repaired.

One rear door a slightly different shade of silver.

Eyo opens the back.

Eyo and Ade load the luggage.

Malik supervises without correcting him.

Almost.

The empty brass urn remains wrapped inside Malik's carry-on.

The birch travel urn stays in his hands.

Eyo closes the rear hatch.

It rebounds.

He lifts it again.

Slams harder.

The latch catches.

EYO
Everything here needs persuasion.

ADE
Malik is going to love it.

INT. LAND CRUISER - MOVING - AFTERNOON

Eyo drives.

Bode beside him.

Malik and Ade in the second row.

Kai behind them among the luggage.

The travel urn rests across Malik's thighs.

Both hands around it.

The air conditioner exhales without conviction.

Eyo strikes the dashboard once.

The fan blows harder.

EYO
You see?

ADE
Violence.

Finally, a system I understand.

Malik loosens the top button of his shirt.

MALIK
How long to the house?

EYO
Depends on road.

MALIK
Approximately.

EYO
Depends how road feels about
approximation.

Bode looks out the window.

Familiar streets arriving faster than memory can receive them.

EYO
Una don chop?

ADE
Three time zones ago.

EYO
That one no be food.

ADE
It had plastic around it.

EYO
Exactly.

EXT. CALABAR STREETS - MOVING - AFTERNOON

The city meets them without introduction.

Low buildings stained by rain.

Deep gutters.

Church signs.

School walls painted with alphabets.

Keke threading between cars.

Market umbrellas holding islands of colour against the white sky.

Children in uniform walk in pairs.

A woman balances a tray of oranges on her head while answering her phone.

Nobody pauses to become scenery.

Kai wipes his lens.

Raises the camera.

Through the glass—

Faces.

Shop fronts.

Power lines crossing and recrossing.

A BARBER looks directly into the lens from his doorway.

Kai lowers the camera.

The barber nods once.

Kai nods back.

Permission negotiated too late.

At a traffic light, a GIRL approaches with cold bottles of water in a basin.

Ade lowers his window.

Eyo names the price before the girl does.

She rolls her eyes.

GIRL
Uncle, allow me do business.

EYO
Do business.

No do robbery.

She hands four bottles through the window.

Ade pays.

Too much.

The girl counts it.

ADE
Keep it.

GIRL
God bless you.

She is gone before Eyo can object.

The light changes.

EYO
Tomorrow, the whole road will know
Canadian people have arrived.

ADE
We prefer philanthropic.

MALIK
You gave her four times the price.

ADE
She had water.

I had Canadian money and no local
judgement.

The exchange was honest.

Kai passes one bottle forward to Bode.

Bode has lowered his window.

Hot air moves across his face.

He breathes it in.

Eyo notices.

EYO
Now you know say you reach.

BODE
I knew at the airport.

EYO
Airport na waiting room.

This one—

He gestures through the windshield.

EYO
—this one is the place.

Bode drinks.

Does not answer.

The city continues around him.

EYO
Everybody dey house.

BODE
Who is everybody?

EYO
Everybody you did not tell not to come.

Ade leans forward.

ADE
How many people is everybody?

EYO
If you count them, somebody will be
insulted.

ADE
Finally.

Family math.

Malik opens the itinerary on his phone.

No address for the house.

Only coordinates.

He enters them.

A blue route appears.

Forty-eight minutes.

He watches the number become fifty-one.

Eyo glances at him in the mirror.

EYO
That thing know road?

MALIK
Satellite does.

EYO
Satellite no enter pothole.

The light changes again.

They move.

INT. LAND CRUISER - MOVING - LATER

Traffic loosens.

Concrete gives way to wider intervals of green.

The brothers' exhaustion settles differently.

Ade's head rests against the window.

Eyes closed.

Not asleep.

Malik studies the route.

Kai watches Bode and Eyo in the rear-view mirror.

Eyo lowers his voice.

EYO
You tell dem?

BODE
No.

Malik looks up.

MALIK
Tell us what?

A MINIBUS cuts across their lane without warning.

Eyo brakes hard.

Water bottles roll beneath the seats.

Ade wakes.

The urn shifts.

Malik catches it immediately.

EYO
This man wan carry all of us enter gutter.

He leans on the horn.

The minibus driver answers with one raised hand and no apology.

Traffic settles.

Malik looks at Bode.

Bode has turned back to the window.

He never answers.

EYO
The house has been closed a long time.

We opened it for you.

MALIK
That is also not an answer.

EYO
It is the answer I can give while
driving.

Malik waits.

Eyo keeps his eyes on the road.

Bode does not rescue either of them.

Ade opens one eye.

ADE
For anyone keeping score, the Canadians
are losing.

Malik looks back at his phone.

The blue route orders them left.

Eyo drives straight.

MALIK
You missed the turn.

EYO
No.

MALIK
The route says left.

EYO
That road washed out last rainy season.

MALIK
The map was updated last month.

EYO
Then the map should come and drive.

Ade closes his eye again.

ADE
It has my vote.

Bode points ahead.

BODE
This way is faster.

Malik looks from the two men to the blue route.

He turns off the screen.

Does not put the phone away.

EXT. OUTSKIRTS ROAD - MOVING - LATE AFTERNOON

The road narrows.

Red earth shows through broken asphalt.

Compounds sit farther apart.

Cassava.

Plantain.

Raffia palms leaning toward unseen water.

Laundry moves on lines behind low walls.

Smoke from cooking fires lies thin beneath the trees.

The Land Cruiser passes a concrete bridge over a brown, slow-moving channel.

Eyo taps the steering wheel toward it.

EYO
Your father jumped from there when he
was fifteen.

All three brothers look.

ADE
On purpose?

BODE
That depends who tells it.

EYO
He told everybody he could swim.

BODE
He could not.

EYO
Still cannot.

The laugh escapes Ade before he can decide whether death permits it.

Kai laughs too.

Malik tries not to.

Fails.

For several seconds—

Solomon is not a secret.

Not an urn.

A frightened fifteen-year-old swallowing river water while his family laughed from a bridge.

The moment passes.

But it leaves the brothers breathing easier.

Kai raises his camera.

Frames the bridge behind them.

This time, he records what is there.

EXT. FOREST ROAD - MOVING - LATER

The sky lowers.

Green crowds both sides of the road.

The air beyond the windows looks almost liquid.

Eyo slows for a deep rut.

The Land Cruiser tilts.

Malik braces the urn against his chest.

Kai looks past him.

Between two enormous trees—

Something too deliberate for the forest.

A LOW STONE STRUCTURE.

No higher than a child.

Half swallowed by the roots of a silk-cotton tree.

At its centre:

A narrow wooden panel.

Dark with age.

Bound once with a strip of faded RED FIBRE.

No sign.

No path visible from the road.

KAI
Slow down.

Eyo brakes gently.

Ade wakes.

MALIK
What happened?

Kai twists toward the rear window.

KAI
There was something in the tree.

Eyo's eyes move to Bode.

Only for a moment.

BODE
What did you see?

KAI
Stone.

Like a door.

Inside the roots.

Eyo drives on.

KAI
Can we stop?

BODE
No.

The answer is immediate.

Not mysterious.

Protective.

Kai looks at him.

KAI
What is it?

BODE
An old boundary.

KAI
For the house?

BODE
Not yours to cross.

KAI
That is not what I asked.

Bode holds his gaze.

BODE
It is what you need to know.

Malik hears the echo of Eyo's answer.

Another closed door disguised as protection.

Kai checks the footage.

Windshield glare.

Leaves.

Motion.

Then—

Three blurred frames of stone held inside roots.

Real.

He pauses on the clearest one.

The wooden panel.

The faded red binding.

Bode looks back.

BODE
Keep the picture if you need it.

Just do not confuse a picture with
permission.

Kai lowers the camera.

KAI
Did Dad know about it?

Bode turns forward.

BODE
Your father knew what boundaries were
for.

Outside, the trees stream past.

Malik studies the back of Bode's head.

MALIK
Did he respect them?

Bode does not answer.

He does not need to.

EXT. OKU FAMILY ROAD - LATE AFTERNOON

The first rain strikes the windshield.

Large drops.

Widely spaced.

Eyo turns off the main road onto packed red earth.

Malik's phone loses the route.

The blue line ends in blank green.

He looks at it.

Then locks the screen.

Ahead—

A metal gate between rendered pillars.

Faded letters remain across the arch:

OKU.

Eyo sounds the horn.

Two short.

One long.

The gate opens before the final note dies.

EXT. OKU FAMILY COMPOUND - CONTINUOUS

The Land Cruiser enters.

The house from the photograph waits at the far end.

White walls weathered toward cream.

A rust-red roof.

Deep veranda.

Green wooden shutters.

Repairs visible beside older repairs.

Not abandoned.

Maintained.

Enduring.

Beside it—

The massive tree.

Larger now.

Its roots have lifted the paving stones and reached toward the veranda.

The compound is already alive.

Children abandon a football game.

Women emerge from the side kitchen carrying covered bowls.

Men rise from plastic chairs beneath the veranda.

Someone calls Bode's name.

Then everyone does.

EYO
You asked who is everybody.

Ade looks at the waiting family.

ADE
I should have worn better shoes.

MALIK
You are wearing shoes.

ADE
Exactly.

The Land Cruiser stops.

For a moment, no one inside moves.

Bode looks at the house.

The tree.

The faces waiting for him.

Eyo switches off the engine.

The air conditioner dies.

Family sound enters all at once.

EYO
You fit come down.

BODE
I know.

EYO
Your body never hear.

Bode opens his door.

The family folds around him.

Hands.

Shoulders.

Names spoken with affection and accusation in equal measure.

Bode disappears into homecoming.

The brothers climb out more slowly.

They are immediately visible as outsiders.

Not because anyone rejects them.

Because everyone recognizes them.

Eyes linger.

Comparisons pass silently from face to face.

Then the family parts for AUNTIE ENO, late sixties.

Strong.

Elegant.

The young Eno from the 1989 photograph, transformed by thirty-seven years without becoming less recognizable.

Solomon and Bode's cousin.

A house key tied into the corner of her wrapper.

She stops before Bode.

ENO
You took your time.

BODE
I know.

Eno touches his face.

Not forgiveness.

Proof.

Then she looks at Malik.

Then Ade.

Then Kai.

ENO
Solomon divided his face among three
children.

Ade glances at his brothers.

ADE
He could have divided the height more
fairly.

Eno considers him.

Then laughs.

The family follows.

Ade's shoulders lower.

His work has begun.

Eno's eyes settle on the padded carry case.

Malik holds it tighter.

She places one palm against the case.

No prayer.

No performance.

Only contact.

ENO
You bring am.

MALIK
We brought him.

The correction matters.

She looks at all three brothers.

Nods.

ENO
Then enter.

Family members reach for luggage.

Malik starts to object.

Stops himself.

He lets a YOUNG MAN take his suitcase.

Not the urn.

One thing at a time.

Kai hangs back.

He removes the creased 1989 photograph from his camera bag.

Holds it against the living house.

Same veranda.

Same shutters.

Same massive tree.

In the photograph, four young people stand before roots that end several feet from the steps.

Solomon.

Bode.

Eno.

The woman whose face was destroyed.

Kai lowers the photograph.

Now—

One root has reached the threshold.

Family streams around it without looking down.

Malik enters first with the travel urn.

Ade follows.

Inside Bode's jacket—

The sealed MiniDV envelope.

Still unopened.

Kai remains outside.

The camera in one hand.

The damaged photograph in the other.

He raises the photograph once more.

Aligns past and present.

The scratched-away face covers the open doorway.

A human-shaped absence filled with the darkness inside the house.

KAI
Who were you?

No answer.

Only family calling his name from within.

Kai lowers the photograph.

Steps over the root.

Enters.

CUT TO BLACK.
